explain this whole --color=always. why isn't this built in by default? of course I don't want to lose colors if piping to grep. or any other time actually.

Gemini said
It feels counterintuitive, right? You’ve spent time configuring a beautiful terminal, and the moment you use a pipe (|), everything turns into dull grey text.

The reason this isn't the default behavior comes down to a long-standing Unix philosophy regarding interoperability and "clean" data.

The "Why": ANSI Escape Codes
Colors in your terminal aren't actually "color properties" of the file; they are invisible ANSI escape codes wrapped around the text.

Plain text: README.md

Colorized text: ^[[32mREADME.md^[[0m (The ^[[32m tells the terminal "start green.")

If eza sent those hidden codes to grep by default, grep would try to match your pattern against those invisible characters. This often breaks scripts, causes weird search results, or results in "garbage" characters appearing in text files if you were to redirect output (e.g., eza > list.txt).

The Default "Auto" Logic
Most modern CLI tools (like eza, ls, and grep) use a setting called --color=auto. Here is how the logic works:

Is the output a TTY? (Are you looking at it directly on a screen?) → Show colors.

Is the output a Pipe or File? (Is it being sent to another program?) → Strip colors.

By stripping colors during a pipe, eza ensures that the next program receives "clean" text it can actually process.

Comparison of Color Flags
Flag	Behavior	Best Use Case
--color=auto	Colors on screen, plain text in pipes.	The standard default for safety.
--color=always	Forces ANSI codes everywhere.	When piping to grep or less -R.
--color=never	Strictly plain text.	Creating clean logs or text lists.
The "Permanent" Fix: Aliases
If you hate typing --color=always every time you pipe, you can make your life easier by adding an alias to your shell configuration file (.bashrc or .zshrc).

However, be careful! If you alias eza to always use --color=always, you might break other scripts. A better move is to create a specific "pipe-friendly" alias:

Bash
# In your .zshrc or .bashrc
alias ezag='eza --color=always --icons | grep'
Now, you can just run ezag "pattern" and get filtered, colorful results instantly.

