Since you're all set on the "why," here is the "how" to make sure your tools actually play nice with those colors.

If you use --color=always and pipe it into other common tools, they might still show you "garbage" text (like ^[[32m) because they don't know how to interpret those color codes.

1. The less Fix
If you have a massive directory and want to scroll through it with colors intact, standard less will fail. You need the -R (Raw control characters) flag:

Bash
eza --color=always -l | less -R
2. The grep Fix
When you pipe eza into grep, grep usually strips its own highlighting unless you tell it not to. To keep both eza colors and grep highlights:

Bash
eza --color=always | grep --color=always "pattern"
3. The "Set and Forget" Aliases
To save your fingers, add these to your ~/.bashrc or ~/.zshrc:

Bash
# Force grep to always show its own colors
export GREP_COLORS='ms=01;31' # Bold red for matches
alias grep='grep --color=auto'

# A specific alias for colored searches
alias ezag='eza --color=always --icons | grep --color=always'
